{"title_page": "Muthoni Likimani", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Muthoni Likimani\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Muthoni Gachanja\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1926}}\n| birth_place   = [[Murang'a District]], [[Kenya]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Kenyan\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Writer, broadcaster\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = ''Passbook Number F. 47927: Women and Mau Mau in Kenya''\n}}\n'''Muthoni Gachanja Likimani''' (born 1926) is a [[Kenya]]n activist and writer, who has published works of both fiction and non-fiction, as well as children's books.<ref name=Beahan /> In her career she has also been a broadcaster, actress, teacher and publisher.<ref name=James /> She was the first Kenyan beauty queen, the first African to establish a public relations firm in Kenya and one of the country's earliest female authors.<ref name=Nation />\n\n==Biography==\nMuthoni Likimani was born and raised in Kahuhia Mission, [[Murang'a District]], Kenya, the daughter of Mariuma Wanjiura and Rev. Levi GochanJa. Her father was one of the first Kenyan Anglican church ministers.<ref name=Bekers>Elisabeth Bekers, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=39JMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA500&lpg=RA2-PA500&dq=%22Likimani,%20Muthoni+Gachanja%22&source=bl&ots=1zco7mtuXv&sig=HIMebm9gD6DRfmMAhM4L2eG1Yyc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH0vK-n-XPAhVhBsAKHePqC40Q6AEIRjAL#v=onepage&q=%22Muthoni%20Likimani%22%20without%20ceasing&f=false \"Likimani, Muthoni Gachanja\"], in Emmanuel Kwaku Akyeampong, Henry Louis Gates, ''Dictionary of African Biography, Volume 6''], Oxford University Press, 2012, pp. 499\u2013500.</ref> She taught at Kahuhia Teachers\u2019 Training College, before undertaking further studies in Britain and Israel, becoming involved  in broadcasting and public relations.<ref name=Nation>Emeka-Mayaka Gekara and Julius Sigei, [http://www.nation.co.ke/lifestyle/weekend/Muthoni-Likimani-Beauty-queen-who-broke-glass-ceiling-/1220-1898188-tqf8ds/index.html \"Muthoni Likimani: Beauty queen who broke glass ceiling\"], ''The Nation'' (Kenya), 28 June 2013.</ref> She went on to become one of the first women producers at the [[Kenya Broadcasting Corporation]], working on women's and children's programmes,<ref name=Beahan>Maxine Beahan, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lvI-Xw5CJdwC&pg=PA296&lpg=PA296&dq=muthoni+likimani&source=bl&ots=530FYo#v=onepage&q=muthoni%20likimani&f=false \"Muthoni Likimani (1926\u2013 )\"], in Pushpa Naidu Parekh and Siga Fatima Jagne, ''Postcolonial African Writers: A Bio-bibliographical Critical Sourcebook'', Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Press, 1998, pp. 296\u2013299.</ref> and was a freelance broadcaster for the [[BBC]].<ref name=Footprints>[http://footprintspress.blogspot.co.uk/2011/11/conversations-with-high-achieving-men_21.html \"Life Journeys\"], Footprints Press, 21 November 2011.</ref> She founded Noni's Publicity, a public relations company that also undertook publishing, such as producing the periodical ''Women of Kenya''.<ref name=Bekers />\n\nHer first novel, ''They Shall Be Chastised'', was published in 1974, followed by ''What Does a Man Want?'' in the same year. In 1985 her third and most important book appeared, ''Passbook Number F. 47927: Women and Mau Mau in Kenya'', its title a reference to her identity number during the [[Mau Mau Uprising|Mau Mau struggle]].<ref name=James>Adeola James, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=95y1BBHDsYMC&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59&dq=muthoni+likimani&source=bl&ots=koAV7W6s-G&sig=-H3TT1mme_Y9cuTeV5s6weX3L0s&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjiw-Xy0-DPAhVlBsAKHSgiAQkQ6AEIaTAQ#v=onepage&q=muthoni%20likimani&f=false \"Muthoni Likimani\"], ''In Their Own Voices: African Women Writers Talk'', James Currey Ltd, 1990, pp. 59\u201362.</ref> It is a fictional work that dramatizes the roles women played and the strategies they adopted in their daily lives during the fight for freedom.<ref name=Beahan />\n\nIn the 1980s, Likimani became a [[Nairobi]] city councillor, which position she held until the government replaced the council with a city commission.<ref name=Bekers /> Her autobiography, ''Fighting Without Ceasing'', was published in 2005.\n\nIn 2007, she received the World YWCA Council Award in recognition of dedicated leadership for her involvement as a Women's Rights Activist.<ref name=Footprints /> In 2014 she was appointed Peace Ambassador in Kenya of The International Forum for the Literature and Culture of Peace (IFLAC).<ref>Solveig Hansen, [https://iflac.wordpress.com/2014/02/18/muthoni-likimani/ \"A strong voice from Kenya: Muthoni Likimani appointed IFLAC Peace Ambassador\"], IFLAC News, 18 February 2014.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nA [[Kikuyu people|Kikuyu]], she married the [[Masai people|Masai]] Dr Jason Clement Likimani, whom she met when he was the Medical Officer of Health at Fort Hall (now Murang'a) District General Hospital. She has said: \"He had been with my brother, Ngumba, at [[Makerere University College]] and he used to come home. He was the only African medical practitioner allowed access to detention camps to treat detainees. And during our visits I was not allowed inside the camps. I would converse across the barbed wire and would sneak in and out letters to detainees\u2019 relatives. That is how I became an unofficial letter carrier even though my husband did not know.\"<ref name=Nation /> They had four children.<ref name=Footprints /> Her husband died in 1989.<ref name=Bekers />\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''They Shall Be Chastised''. Nairobi: East African Literature Bureau, 1974. Kenya Literature Bureau, 1991, {{ISBN|978-9966440945}}.\n* ''What Does a Man Want?'' Nairobi: Kenya Literature Bureau, 1974. Noni's Publicity, 2001, {{ISBN|978-9966441201}}\n* ''Passbook Number F. 47927: Women and Mau Mau in Kenya''. Basingstoke and London: Palgrave Macmillan, 1985, {{ISBN|978-0333379455}}. Noni's Publicity, 2001, {{ISBN|978-9966967206}}.\n* ''Women of Kenya: In the Decade of Development''. Nairobi: Noni's Publicity, 1985.\n* ''Fighting Without Ceasing'', Nairobi: Noni's Publicity, 2005, {{ISBN|978-9966967268}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://africacreates.net/2013/07/25/muthoni-likimani-story-of-a-legend/ \"Muthoni Likimani: Story of a Legend\"], ''Africa Creates'', 25 July 2013.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R5fKteJyib8 \"Capital Talk Muthoni Likimani\"], K24TV interview Part 1; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tOFkW-oRq7Q \"Capital Talk Muthoni Likimani Part 2\"], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6zjB14oozA4 \"Capital Talk Muthoni Likimani Part 3\"], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4OXrNEA0ZLg \"Capital Talk Muthoni Likimani Part 4\"], YouTube.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Likimani, Muthoni}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kenyan writers]]\n[[Category:Kenyan women writers]]\n[[Category:Children's writers]]\n[[Category:Kenyan activists]]\n[[Category:Kenyan women activists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Muthoni Likimani\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Muthoni Gachanja\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1926}}\n| birth_place   = [[Murang'a District]], [[Kenya]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Kenyan\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Writer, broadcaster\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = ''Passbook Number F. 47927: Women and Mau Mau in Kenya''\n}}\n'''Muthoni Gachanja Likimani''' (born 1926) is a [[Kenya]]n activist and writer, who has published works of both fiction and non-fiction, as well as children's books.<ref name=Beahan /> In her career she has also been a broadcaster, actress, teacher and publisher.<ref name=James /> She was the first Kenyan beauty queen, the first African to establish a public relations firm in Kenya and one of the country's earliest female authors.<ref name=Nation />\n\n==Biography==\nMuthoni Likimani was born and raised in Kahuhia Mission, [[Murang'a District]], Kenya, the daughter of Mariuma Wanjiura and Rev. Levi GochanJa. Her father was one of the first Kenyan Anglican church ministers.<ref name=Bekers>Elisabeth Bekers, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=39JMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA500&lpg=RA2-PA500&dq=%22Likimani,%20Muthoni+Gachanja%22&source=bl&ots=1zco7mtuXv&sig=HIMebm9gD6DRfmMAhM4L2eG1Yyc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH0vK-n-XPAhVhBsAKHePqC40Q6AEIRjAL#v=onepage&q=%22Muthoni%20Likimani%22%20without%20ceasing&f=false \"Likimani, Muthoni Gachanja\"], in Emmanuel Kwaku Akyeampong, Henry Louis Gates, ''Dictionary of African Biography, Volume 6''], Oxford University Press, 2012, pp. 499\u2013500.</ref> She taught at Kahuhia Teachers\u2019 Training College, before undetaking further studies in Britain and Israel, becoming involved  in broadcasting and public relations.<ref name=Nation>Emeka-Mayaka Gekara and Julius Sigei, [http://www.nation.co.ke/lifestyle/weekend/Muthoni-Likimani-Beauty-queen-who-broke-glass-ceiling-/1220-1898188-tqf8ds/index.html \"Muthoni Likimani: Beauty queen who broke glass ceiling\"], ''The Nation'' (Kenya), 28 June 2013.</ref> She went on to become one of the first women producers at the [[Kenya Broadcasting Corporation]], working on women's and children's programmes,<ref name=Beahan>Maxine Beahan, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lvI-Xw5CJdwC&pg=PA296&lpg=PA296&dq=muthoni+likimani&source=bl&ots=530FYo#v=onepage&q=muthoni%20likimani&f=false \"Muthoni Likimani (1926\u2013 )\"], in Pushpa Naidu Parekh and Siga Fatima Jagne, ''Postcolonial African Writers: A Bio-bibliographical Critical Sourcebook'', Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Press, 1998, pp. 296\u2013299.</ref> and was a freelance broadcaster for the [[BBC]].<ref name=Footprints>[http://footprintspress.blogspot.co.uk/2011/11/conversations-with-high-achieving-men_21.html \"Life Journeys\"], Footprints Press, 21 November 2011.</ref> She founded Noni's Publicity, a public relations company that also undertook publishing, such as producing the periodical ''Women of Kenya''.<ref name=Bekers />\n\nHer first novel, ''They Shall Be Chastised'', was published in 1974, followed by ''What Does a Man Want?'' in the same year. In 1985 her third and most important book appeared, ''Passbook Number F. 47927: Women and Mau Mau in Kenya'', its title a reference to her identity number during the [[Mau Mau Uprising|Mau Mau struggle]].<ref name=James>Adeola James, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=95y1BBHDsYMC&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59&dq=muthoni+likimani&source=bl&ots=koAV7W6s-G&sig=-H3TT1mme_Y9cuTeV5s6weX3L0s&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjiw-Xy0-DPAhVlBsAKHSgiAQkQ6AEIaTAQ#v=onepage&q=muthoni%20likimani&f=false \"Muthoni Likimani\"], ''In Their Own Voices: African Women Writers Talk'', James Currey Ltd, 1990, pp. 59\u201362.</ref> It is a fictional work that dramatizes the roles women played and the strategies they adopted in their daily lives during the fight for freedom.<ref name=Beahan />\n\nIn the 1980s, Likimani became a [[Nairobi]] city councillor, which position she held until the government replaced the council with a city commission.<ref name=Bekers /> Her autobiography, ''Fighting Without Ceasing'', was published in 2005.\n\nIn 2007, she received the World YWCA Council Award in recognition of dedicated leadership for her involvement as a Women's Rights Activist.<ref name=Footprints /> In 2014 she was appointed Peace Ambassador in Kenya of The International Forum for the Literature and Culture of Peace (IFLAC).<ref>Solveig Hansen, [https://iflac.wordpress.com/2014/02/18/muthoni-likimani/ \"A strong voice from Kenya: Muthoni Likimani appointed IFLAC Peace Ambassador\"], IFLAC News, 18 February 2014.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nA [[Kikuyu people|Kikuyu]], she married the [[Masai people|Masai]] Dr Jason Clement Likimani, whom she met when he was the Medical Officer of Health at Fort Hall (now Murang'a) District General Hospital. She has said: \"He had been with my brother, Ngumba, at [[Makerere University College]] and he used to come home. He was the only African medical practitioner allowed access to detention camps to treat detainees. And during our visits I was not allowed inside the camps. I would converse across the barbed wire and would sneak in and out letters to detainees\u2019 relatives. That is how I became an unofficial letter carrier even though my husband did not know.\"<ref name=Nation /> They had four children.<ref name=Footprints /> Her husband died in 1989.<ref name=Bekers />\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''They Shall Be Chastised''. Nairobi: East African Literature Bureau, 1974. Kenya Literature Bureau, 1991, {{ISBN|978-9966440945}}.\n* ''What Does a Man Want?'' Nairobi: Kenya Literature Bureau, 1974. Noni's Publicity, 2001, {{ISBN|978-9966441201}}\n* ''Passbook Number F. 47927: Women and Mau Mau in Kenya''. Basingstoke and London: Palgrave Macmillan, 1985, {{ISBN|978-0333379455}}. Noni's Publicity, 2001, {{ISBN|978-9966967206}}.\n* ''Women of Kenya: In the Decade of Development''. Nairobi: Noni's Publicity, 1985.\n* ''Fighting Without Ceasing'', Nairobi: Noni's Publicity, 2005, {{ISBN|978-9966967268}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://africacreates.net/2013/07/25/muthoni-likimani-story-of-a-legend/ \"Muthoni Likimani: Story of a Legend\"], ''Africa Creates'', 25 July 2013.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R5fKteJyib8 \"Capital Talk Muthoni Likimani\"], K24TV interview Part 1; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tOFkW-oRq7Q \"Capital Talk Muthoni Likimani Part 2\"], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6zjB14oozA4 \"Capital Talk Muthoni Likimani Part 3\"], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4OXrNEA0ZLg \"Capital Talk Muthoni Likimani Part 4\"], YouTube.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Likimani, Muthoni}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kenyan writers]]\n[[Category:Kenyan women writers]]\n[[Category:Children's writers]]\n[[Category:Kenyan activists]]\n[[Category:Kenyan women activists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women writers]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Typo fixing, replaced: undetaking \u2192 undertaking", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muthoni_Likimani"}
{"title_page": "Mount Steller (Aleutian Range)", "text_new": "{{About|the peak in the [[Aleutian Range]]|the peak in the [[Chugach Mountains]]|Mount Steller (Chugach Mountains)}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Mount Steller\n| photo = Mount Denison and Mount Steller.jpg\n| photo_caption = Mount Steller (at right) in August 2003 (Mount Denison is to the left)\n| elevation_ft = 7454\n| elevation_ref =\n| prominence_ft = 1600\n| prominence_ref =\n| map = Alaska\n| map_size = 260\n| map_caption = Alaska\n| label_position =\n| location = [[Katmai National Park and Preserve]], [[Alaska]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| range = [[Aleutian Range]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|58|25|47|N|154|23|29|W|type:mountain_region:US_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n| range_coordinates = \n| type = [[Stratovolcano]]\n| volcanic_arc/belt = [[Aleutian Arc]]\n}}\n\n'''Mount Steller''' is a [[stratovolcano]] in [[Katmai National Park]] in [[Alaska]], [[United States]]. It is part of the [[Aleutian Range]] and is located on the [[Alaska Peninsula]].\n\nThe mountain was presumably named for the naturalist [[Georg Wilhelm Steller]]. While evidence is uncertain, the volcano is believed to have erupted during the [[Holocene]] epoch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://volcano.si.edu/volcano.cfm?vn=312220|title=Global Volcanism Program {{!}} Steller|website=volcano.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.topozone.com/map.asp?lat=58.4298&lon=-154.3914&s=500&size=l&symshow=n&datum=nad83&layer=DRG250 Mount Steller on Topozone] (Note that the mountain name is misspelled \"Stellar\" on this map.)\n* {{cite gvp | vnum=1102-22- | title=Steller}}\n\n[[File:Mount Steller (Aleutian Range).jpg|thumb|center|500px|Mount Steller from the east]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steller, Mount (Aleutian Range)}}\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of the United States]]\n[[Category:Aleutian Range]]\n\n\n{{LakeandPeninsulaAK-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the peak in the [[Aleutian Range]]|the peak in the [[Chugach Mountains]]|Mount Steller (Chugach Mountains)}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Mount Steller\n| photo = Mount Denison and Mount Steller.jpg\n| photo_caption = Mount Steller (at right) in August 2003 (Mount Denison is to the left)\n| elevation_ft = 7454\n| elevation_ref =\n| prominence_ft = 1600\n| prominence_ref =\n| map = Alaska\n| map_size = 260\n| map_caption = Alaska\n| label_position =\n| location = [[Katmai National Park and Preserve]], [[Alaska]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| range = [[Aleutian Range]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|58|25|47|N|154|23|29|W|type:mountain_region:US_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n| range_coordinates = \n| type = [[Stratovolcano]]\n| volcanic_arc/belt = [[Aleutian Arc]]\n}}\n\n'''Mount Steller''' is a [[stratovolcano]] in [[Katmai National Park]] in [[Alaska]], [[United States]]. It is part of the [[Aleutian Range]] and is located on the [[Alaska Peninsula]].\n\nThe mountain was presumably named for the naturalist [[Georg Wilhelm Steller]]. While evidence is uncertain, the volcano is believed to have erupted during the [[Holocene]] epoch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://volcano.si.edu/volcano.cfm?vn=312220|title=Global Volcanism Program {{!}} Steller|website=volcano.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.topozone.com/map.asp?lat=58.4298&lon=-154.3914&s=500&size=l&symshow=n&datum=nad83&layer=DRG250 Mount Steller on Topozone] (Note that the mountain name is misspelled \"Stellar\" on this map.)\n* {{cite gvp | vnum=1102-22- | title=Steller}}\n\n[[File:Mount Steller (Aleutian Range).jpg|thumb|center|500px|Mount Steller from the east]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steller, 